column44: "'When visiting the maternity day unit due to spotting, the midwife made me feel like I was lying as she didn’t find any traces of blood, even though my husband & I both witnessed it & it happened again later that evening after I’d been sent home, we rang but they told us to just stay home & monitor the bleeding. She also left me for 30mins-1 hour without monitoring after putting me in an assessment room purely because I was a “rare low risk pregnancy” so I wasn’t a priority to them at all. She left my husband & I feeling like we’d wasted every bodies time."

column102: During our stay with his jaundice, I was 2 days PP & extremely engorged & in an immense amount of pain. None of the nurses would help me, they just handed me a pump & left me to figure it out for myself. I did manage to see some local BF support workers but they weren’t all that helpful. Then during another stay in hospital, where he ended up being nil by mouth, my supply decreased massively & I struggled to get it back up again so I had to stop.

column125: "'I was left to sleep on a camp bed during our stay on the children’s ward for my babies jaundice. I was in agony with my stitches & also my breasts being so engorged, nobody would help or listen to me as I wasn’t the patient. I was just given more pillows even though I told them they weren’t helping. I had 8 pillows! I was handed a breast pump finally but wasn’t told how to use it & only given a single attachment. I was pumping every 20-30 minutes for about an hour each time. I was crying in pain & wasn’t able to sit or lie down so I wasn’t sleeping either."

column125: "'My baby was born premature. I was in shock, so was my husband. We could not get along during that time and that made things more difficult and painful. I was asking for mental health support. I just wanted someone to talk to, but did not have anyone talking to me. At some point I was questioned about my mental health but that was done in very clinical way and I felt I could not trust the person. Due to tensions with my husband I felt like neonatal nurses were getting too involved. In two occasions two different nurses who were younger than me would sit me down and suggest to get divorced. Only after conversation with a matron and my husband our relationship started to improve. I was very nervous and stressed, that affected my milk supply, but I keept expressing. At the end when going home from neonatal unit I was given bag full with my frozen expressed milk, that made me think that baby has mostly receiving formula. Also after giving birth when they removed me from intensive care to Rowan ward at first I was put in to room with other mums and their babies. That was so painful I started to cry straight away and then I was moved to different room where I did not need to see other mums and babies together. In neonatal unit during lunch time I noticed that other mums would also benefit form someone with mental health support to speak to. They were also traumatised and talking about their experiences. Having someone professional to talk to about emotions I was going through at that moment would have helped me a lot. Also if only my husband would have an option to talk to someone as well at the time it would also had helped. Now everything is fine and looking back I can see that we were in shock and people around us was not very trained to support us. Also discharge was very sudden and I was told on the day that I am going home today with my baby. I obviously was happy but I wish I was prepared for this like maybe days before. That I could plan things better and make home ready for baby. It might sound funny, but when baby is in neonatal nothing can be done because everything is about expressing milk and being near the baby in the hospital."
